===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|melior||better|lang=la}} {{suffix||ism|lang=en}}. Reportedly coined by British author [[w:George Eliot|George Eliot]] in her letters, published in 1877.

===Pronunciation===
*{{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈmiːlɪəɹɪz(ə)m/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The view or [[doctrine]] that the [[world]] can be [[improve]]d through human [[effort]] (often understood as an [[intermediate]] outlook between [[optimism]] and [[pessimism]]). {{defdate|from 19th c.}}
#*'''1966''' May 6, "[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,901869,00.html Forever Beginning]," ''Time'':
#*: At the convention, the official mood was traditional Methodist '''meliorism'''.
#*'''2002''', {{w|Colin Jones (historian)|Colin Jones}}, ''The Great Nation'', Penguin 2003, page 371:
#*:Enclaves of meritocratic and virtuous sociability, the lodges exuded [...] a thoroughgoing '''meliorism'''.
 
